{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17493432","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17493432"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T07:10:37+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T07:10:37+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"1321"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"1321","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/1321"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.38,0.04,0.2,0.14,0.24]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"1321"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"107490"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"1321","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/1321"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"1321"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"89970"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"10"},{"type":"tags","id":"24"},{"type":"tags","id":"66"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"76"},{"type":"tags","id":"1027"},{"type":"tags","id":"2982"},{"type":"tags","id":"3033"},{"type":"tags","id":"4943"},{"type":"tags","id":"12919"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"460"},{"type":"contributions","id":"520"},{"type":"contributions","id":"1266"},{"type":"contributions","id":"1653"},{"type":"contributions","id":"7389"},{"type":"contributions","id":"37563"},{"type":"contributions","id":"38470"},{"type":"contributions","id":"39546"},{"type":"contributions","id":"40042"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"107490","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/107490"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 40-year-old woman presents to the Emergency Department with severe depression and catatonia requiring hospital admission. She has a medical history of bipolar affective disorder, hypertension, and asthma. Her regular medications are valproate 500 mg twice daily, temazepam 5 mg nocte for sleep, perindopril 5 mg daily, and salbutamol inhaler when required. She does not take any other medications. She appears withdrawn with minimal spontaneous movement and speech.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EOn examination, she has waxy flexibility and maintains uncomfortable postures. Her vital signs are within normal limits. She is scheduled to undergo electroconvulsive therapy.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most appropriate medication adjustment before commencing electroconvulsive therapy?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Cease temazepam and valproate","Cease salbutamol and perindopril","Cease temazepam only","Cease valproate only","No medication adjustment is required"],"correctOptions":[0],"correctResponses":[],"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThis patient presents with severe bipolar depression with catatonic features requiring electroconvulsive therapy (ECT). Medication review prior to commencing ECT is essential to optimise treatment efficacy and safety.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ECease temazepam and valproate\u003C/strong\u003E is the most appropriate option. Both benzodiazepines like temazepam and anticonvulsants like valproate have anticonvulsant properties that raise seizure threshold and reduce seizure duration, potentially compromising ECT effectiveness. They should therefore be discontinued before ECT treatment begins to allow for adequate seizure activity during the procedure.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ECease salbutamol and perindopril\u003C/strong\u003E would be inappropriate and potentially harmful. These medications manage the patient\u0027s asthma and hypertension respectively and are unrelated to neurological function. Discontinuing them could lead to exacerbation of these conditions without providing any benefit for ECT efficacy.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ECease temazepam only\u003C/strong\u003E addresses only part of the issue. While benzodiazepines should be discontinued before ECT, valproate also significantly raises seizure threshold and would interfere with ECT efficacy. Both medications need to be ceased.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ECease valproate only\u003C/strong\u003E similarly addresses only part of the issue. Both valproate and temazepam can interfere with seizure induction during ECT and should be discontinued.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ENo medication adjustment is required\u003C/strong\u003E is incorrect as both temazepam and valproate can significantly impair the efficacy of ECT by raising seizure threshold. Continuing these medications would likely result in inadequate seizure duration or failed seizure induction during ECT.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EAfter the acute course of ECT is completed and the patient\u0027s depression has improved, medication management requires careful consideration. Mood stabilisers would typically be reintroduced towards the end of the ECT course. Lithium is generally not started until ECT is finishing due to the risk of post-ECT delirium, while valproate and other anticonvulsants are delayed due to their effects on seizure threshold. An atypical antipsychotic could also be considered for prophylaxis once her motor symptoms have improved. This staged approach to medication reintroduction balances the need for ongoing mood stabilisation with the requirements of effective ECT treatment.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Benzodiazepines and anticonvulsants should be discontinued before ECT as they raise seizure threshold and reduce treatment efficacy.","Medications unrelated to neurological function (e.g., antihypertensives, bronchodilators) can generally be continued during ECT.","Severe bipolar depression with catatonia is an indication for ECT."],"references":["Haskett RF, Loo C. Adjunctive psychotropic medications during electroconvulsive therapy in the treatment of depression, mania, and schizophrenia. J ECT 2010; 26:196. Available at: https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/20805728/","Greenberg RM, Pettinati HM. Benzodiazepines and Electroconvulsive Therapy. Convuls Ther 1993; 9:262. Available at: https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/11941222/","Sienaert P, Peuskens J. Anticonvulsants during electroconvulsive therapy: review and recommendations. J ECT 2007; 23:120. Available at: https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/17548985/"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"89970"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"1321"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"89970","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/89970"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-06-30T10:20:07+09:30","updatedAt":"2025-06-30T10:20:45+09:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"1321"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"107490"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"10","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/10"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83c\udfad","name":"Psychiatry","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":"2024-11-21T09:49:46+10:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"1"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"24","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/24"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83d\ude91","name":"Emergency Medicine","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"5"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"66","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/66"},"attrib